# Chunk 8
# (JML) I took a bit of a different approach (I blame my SQL background). Based on the question, I interpreted the ask to be to replace the state abbreviation in `pneumoniaFull` with the full state name. To me, the full name was available in the `state.fips` dataframe, but I'd need to only get the characters to the left of the colon (:). I'd also need to reduce the resulting list to unique values. So, `pneumoniaFull_testing` is the result of 1) creating a helper table with just state names, 2) creating a 2nd table with just unique records, 3) replacing the 2-letter abbr with the full state name found in the 2nd table. Hope this approach doesn't go against the lesson's intention. I have called this df "pneumoniaFull_testing" to keep it separate from the rest of the Demo code.
library(dplyr)
state.fips_noIsland <- state.fips %>%
mutate(polyname = trimws(sub(":.*", "", polyname))) %>%
select(abb, polyname)
state.fips_noIsland_unique <- unique(state.fips_noIsland)
pneumoniaFull_testing <- pneumoniaFull %>%
mutate(State = ifelse(State %in% names(state.fips_noIsland_unique),
state.fips_noIsland_unique[pneumonia$State],
state.fips_noIsland_unique$polyname))
view(pneumoniaFull_testing)
